<subSubSection box="[151,380,546,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,380,546,573]" box="[151,380,546,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,380,546,573]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,380,546,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1920" box="[207,298,546,573]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Opostega" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="velifera">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,298,546,573]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">velifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,619,1005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
Externally, species are characterized by the brown frontal tuft and dark pattern of the forewing, densely covered with brown and pale brown scales (except for the brownish cream costal margin in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[1094,1208,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sumbae">
<emphasis box="[1094,1208,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">P. sumbae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and three yellowish cream spots along the costa in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[498,611,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="velifera">
<emphasis box="[498,611,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">P. velifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); apical strigulae and apical dot absent (
<figureCitation box="[1066,1132,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). In the male genitalia, the uncus is comprised of two large, triangular lateral lobes; the gnathos is a triangular plate with a well-developed, slender caudal process; and the vinculum is without a juxta (
<figureCitation box="[838,905,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). In the female genitalia, apophyses long; anal papillae are modified into a single, wide but short lobe (
<figureCitation box="[779,845,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); the signum is strongly developed, lamellar, curved (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[161,274,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="velifera">
<emphasis box="[161,274,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">P. velifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[328,473,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[328,473,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">P. nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), or weakly developed (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[747,860,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sumbae">
<emphasis box="[747,860,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">P. sumbae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,619,1005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
From other groups of the Oriental (or Neotropical) 
<taxonomicName box="[785,955,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[785,955,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Pseudopostega</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[1013,1099,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="velifera">
<emphasis box="[1013,1099,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">velifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is distinguished by the unique combination of a dark forewing and frontal tuft, absence of a juxta in the male genitalia, and single-lobed anal papillae in the female genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1379,979,1005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,619,1005]" box="[199,1379,979,1005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
Distribution. Currently the group is comprised of three species distributed in 
<collectingCountry box="[1062,1122,979,1005]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1134,1204,979,1005]" name="Nepal" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Nepal</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1262,1375,979,1005]" name="Indonesia" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
